===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*ḱerd-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|herte}}, from {{inh|en|ang|heorte||heart}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hertô||heart}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*ḱḗr||heart}}. Cognate with {{cog|stq|Haat}}, {{cog|fy|hert}}, {{cog|nl|hart}}, {{cog|nds-de|Hart}}, {{cog|de|Herz}}, {{cog|is|hjarta}}, {{cog|la|cor|cor, cordis}}, {{cog|grc|καρδία}}, {{cog|sa|हृद्|tr=hṛ́d}}, {{cog|cy|craidd}}, {{cog|ga|croí}}, {{cog|hy|սիրտ}}, {{cog|ru|се́рдце}}, and {{cog|lt|širdis}}. {{doublet|en|cardia}}.

Most of the modern figurative senses (such as passion or compassion, spirit, inmost feelings, especially love, affection, and courage) were present in Old English. However, the meaning "inner part of something" dates from the early 14th century.<ref name="etymonline">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

The verb sense “to love” is from the 1977 {{w|I Love New York|I ❤ NY}} advertising campaign.<ref name="etymonline"/>

